Starting a clothing looks like fun & at times it is but here’s a few things I wish I knew when I first started.
-
The best brands are simple. They know who they serve and what products they sell. I always say the best restaurants have one page menus
-
The best brands are built over time layered up on years of failures. This is part of the course.
-
Things take a lot longer than you think.
-
There will be ups and downs in in business. You’ll learn the most from the low parts though. The highs are fun as well ☺️
-
The longer I’m in the business the more I realise it’s more about perseverance than smarts. Hold on & keep going.
-
Life rewards the consistent!

Today, streetwear shoppers have broader tastes, which means more competition and more variety, as consumers decide where to direct their money.

While the market for brands like Supreme, Off-White and Palace has cooled, it’s still moving. What’s changed is the streetwear shopper is no longer a monolithic, head-to-toe brand loyalist. Instead, retailers and other experts say the young consumers who might have only bought graphic T-shirts and hoodies a few years ago are embracing a diverse wardrobe that mixes streetwear, heritage brands and traditional menswear or luxury.

@cactusplantfleamarket breaks all of streetwear's rules and only ends up better for it. In this industry, successful brands usually keep things simple, exclusive, and understated, quietly adding a few collaborations to their seasonal lineups. Not CPFM.⁠
⁠
On June 26, CPFM teased a collaboration with family-friendly animated flick @despicableme 4, comprising ultra-approachable logo wear. Earlier that week, models at @junyawatanabe's collaboration-heavy Spring/Summer 2025 menswear show clutched CPFM co-created accessories. These diverse partnerships showcase CPFM's unique ability to maintain cultural cachet while spanning both mass-market and high-fashion realms.⁠
⁠
Generally, streetwear brands fall into two categories: those frequently releasing mediocre merch with well-paying partners, and those whose rare collaborations become collector's items. CPFM defies this dichotomy, shifting seamlessly from McDonald's meals to Nike sneakers to one-off pop-ups without depleting its coveted clout.⁠
⁠
Founded by former @pharrell assistant Cynthia Lu in 2015, CPFM maintains a low profile despite its reach. It sparingly drops in-house creations via a bare-bones website and vacant Instagram page, letting partners and admirers handle promotion.⁠
⁠
Despicable Me is the first CPFM partnership that feels a little left-field.⁠
But, again, CPFM bends the subject to its will. The cartoonish characters, kid-ish quirk, and goofy colors fit within the CPFM world.⁠
⁠
CPFM has clearly earned enough cultural capital to legitimize almost anything. What's next?⁠
⁠
✍️: @trasparenti⁠
📷️: @cactusplantfleamarket

Starting a clothing looks like fun & at times it is but here’s a few things I wish I knew when I first started.
-
The best brands are simple. They know who they serve and what products they sell. I always say the best restaurants have one page menus
-
The best brands are built over time layered up on years of failures. This is part of the course.
-
Things take a lot longer than you think.
-
There will be ups and downs in in business. You’ll learn the most from the low parts though. The highs are fun as well ☺️
-
The longer I’m in the business the more I realise it’s more about perseverance than smarts. Hold on & keep going.
-
Life rewards the consistent!

Caption:
Think of these numbers next time you go clothes shopping! 

Fascinating piece of research in the Telegraph today by Chloe Hamilton (not on Instagram anywhere I could find - but respect) showing the average RESALE value of different women’s clothing brands on @vinted 

Basically, 10% if you’re lucky! 😮 

Also - despite the alluring headline, the seller’s net profit was £38. Travelling around car boot sales buying clothes to trade takes time (I wonder if she made the minimum wage?) But clearly, she had fun. And a great way, frankly, to teach older kids the value of money. 

I am about to drop off a bag of clothes at my local @scopecharity shop. Yes, I could probably make £38 if I listed them all on Vinted, but it’s too much faff. Plus I’ve filled in a donor’s form so the charity can have the Gift Aid on top 💷

However, I do have saved searches on Vinted for my favourite brands and dress size: as the above graphic shows, you clearly want to be a buyer, not a seller, on this platform! 

Would love to hear your thoughts - Chloe’s article is in today’s Telegraph and on their app 👗 

#vinted #vinteduk #reselling

Caption:
"Aesthetics" and trends do not give you the right to shop from exploited labour ✨

When it comes to fashion designing, aesthetics comes 3rd when creating a garment. First is purpose, second is material. 

It is insane vanity to pin where we buy our clothes on aesthetics. If you really cared about ethical practices you wouldn't care about the aesthetic. 

I don't look aesthetic everyday. Most weeks I'll wear the same dress, and I won't even pair it with jewellery or accessories. I will just wear it because it serves its purpose, clothing me.

I hate the "I deserve trendy clothes" argument. No one deserves well curated aesthetics. But EVERYONE deserves fair working conditions and fair pay 🤌

#sustainablefashion #ethicalfashion #sizeinclusivefashion #plussizefashion #corsetry 

Do you think we have the right to trendy clothes? Or is it a privilege to have trendy clothes? 👇

Starting a clothing looks like fun & at times it is but here’s a few things I wish I knew when I first started.
-
The best brands are simple. They know who they serve and what products they sell. I always say the best restaurants have one page menus
-
The best brands are built over time layered up on years of failures. This is part of the course.
-
Things take a lot longer than you think.
-
There will be ups and downs in in business. You’ll learn the most from the low parts though. The highs are fun as well ☺️
-
The longer I’m in the business the more I realise it’s more about perseverance than smarts. Hold on & keep going.
-
Life rewards the consistent!

Breaking Convention: Filipino Brands Fusing Traditional & Contemporary Styles

As the Philippine fashion industry continues to emerge, more local fashion brands are now blending traditional and sustainable features with modern styles. This local fashion brand is bringing Filipino artistry to Tokyo ✨

@idyllicsummers is taking over Tokyo’s fashion scene, along with contemporaries @bagasaostudios @jmakitalojewelry @kelvinmmorales and @proudrace!

From May 24 to 28, they’re joining their first-ever international pop-up at the fashion-forward Esmeralda Serviced Department in Shibuya.

The brand’s capsule collection takes from Japanese aesthetics with inspiration from designers like #IsseyMiyake and master pattern cutter #ShingoSato. But Idyllic Summers puts a twist—celebrating Filipino craftsmanship, artisan collaborations, and heritage textiles piña and hablon. 

It’s as brand founder Steffi Cua says, “It’s about communicating our personal take on the identity of the Philippines.”

Story by @lalasingian

Crafted with locally-sourced materials such as abaca, rattan, leather, and even recycled fabrics, Filipino bags are not only beautiful but also eco-conscious. Whether you're seeking a casual tote for everyday use or a luxurious handbag to elevate your ensemble, there's a Filipino-made piece that's perfect for you.

"Bold, provocative, a bit avant-garde," this was how stylist #LynAlumno described the process of styling #NadineLustre. For #ParisFashionWeek, Lustre was seen in archival pieces from national artist #SalvacionLimHiggins, #RajoLaurel, #Prada, and #Mugler, as well as contemporary Filipino brands #.ARCHIVES and #RafaWorldwide. Alumno's goal in putting together these looks was to showcase Filipino fashion in a fresh way, with a diverse range that included pieces from 1967, 2013, and the present. "There’s something so satisfying about wearing anything locally made and being able to put a spotlight on the people who made it when you’re in a place far from home. I’m glad that Nadine and I are on the same page with this one," said Alumno.

I find it very rare ( a unicorn literally) to find a Filipino brand that’s full on circular. And what @bayofoundationph @bayoatelier did is pretty groundbreaking and it demonstrates how Filipino brands can lead the global movement toward regenerative fashion systems.

Fully circular fashion brands don’t just stop when you throw clothing away. It’s a cycle, so if you’re buying clothes, making them, expecting them to be in a landfill, your chain of being a #sustainable brand is broken. 

Every step to save the planet starts from producing even cotton or linen or the agriculture side of fashion, it has to start at the ideation stage.

Starting a clothing looks like fun & at times it is but here’s a few things I wish I knew when I first started.
-
The best brands are simple. They know who they serve and what products they sell. I always say the best restaurants have one page menus
-
The best brands are built over time layered up on years of failures. This is part of the course.
-
Things take a lot longer than you think.
-
There will be ups and downs in in business. You’ll learn the most from the low parts though. The highs are fun as well ☺️
-
The longer I’m in the business the more I realise it’s more about perseverance than smarts. Hold on & keep going.
-
Life rewards the consistent!".

You guys asked, so we listened. If you’re an aspiring brand owner or clothing designer in the making, this post is for YOU 🫵🏼💞

We work with clothing brands from all over Australia. That, combined with our own internal experience in the fashion industry has given us a pretty unique point of view into the business of fashion.

Unfortunately, lots of brand owners fail before they even start. 

It’s usually simply got to do with a lack of strategy which comes just from a lack of know-how 🤷‍♀️

So if you’re struggling with how to get started, take these three tactics into consideration and decide which one is gonna work best for your brand: 

💞The Presale Method: Make it before you spend it

💞 The Clout Method: build the hype then monetize 

💞Balls-to-the-walls Method: Full campaign style ball-out

These three methods are tried, tested, and true but make sure you pick the one that’s best for your brand - only you can know that! 

You can read the complete blog through the link in our bio but be sure to like and follow for more free game 🏀💘

No Gatekeeping in 2025, Here’s Some Free Game for your Brand! 🎯

We asked 5 Top Clothing Brands what they wish they knew before starting out, and here’s what they said:

1️⃣ Know your WHY, or the streets will humble you.

2️⃣ Storytelling sells, make your brand more than just clothes.

3️⃣ Virgil’s 3% rule—do your homework & add your signature.

4️⃣ Document the grind, people love the journey.

5️⃣ Quality over quantity, always.

6️⃣ 80% of your sales will come from 20% of your products—focus!

7️⃣ Sell the lifestyle, not just the product.

8️⃣ Clean visuals = more sales. Learn the basics of photography.

9️⃣ Packaging & presentation? Non-negotiable. First impressions count!

🔟 Automated emails = passive bag. Don’t sleep on it.

This Thrift Store has lost it’s mind! 🤪

Now I can hear the comments already! “It’s social medias fault! It’s resellers fault! Thrift stores have caught on because of videos online!”

Yes, I agree that videos do teach these stores what brands to mark up in some cases. But so does researching sold listings online. Even without the videos, any store could figure out what brands are selling by looking up solds on eBay. It’s not hard for anyone to figure out what’s selling well.

What I will say is this is a clear example of a greedy thrift store. No videos or social media influencers are telling you to pick up George or Old Navy. This store got all that for free, yet they are deciding to overcharge for it. And not even taking the time to condition check it for stains or flaws…WILD!

Even though this store was overpriced, I was able to find a few hidden gems. I’ll share that in part 2 😄
